excerpt: Museum with interactive exhibits dedicated to the Battle of Gettysburg, plus cupola tours.
detail_description: The Seminary Ridge Museum and Education Center is housed in Schmucker Hall, a historic building with a significant role in the Battle of Gettysburg. Visitors can explore interactive exhibits dedicated to the battle and its aftermath. One of the main attractions is the opportunity to climb to the open-air cupola, offering panoramic views similar to those seen by Union General John Buford on the eve of the battle.
name: Seminary Ridge Museum and Education Center
address: Valentine Hall, 61 Seminary Ridge, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

excerpt: Museum dedicated to Gettysburg civilian casualty Jennie Wade with exhibits on domestic wartime life.
detail_description: The Jennie Wade House in Gettysburg is a museum dedicated to the memory of Jennie Wade, a civilian casualty during the Civil War. The house offers exhibits on domestic wartime life and tells the poignant story of Jennie's untimely death. Preserved just as it looked in 1863, each room reflects the sudden shift from normal life during those three days.
name: Jennie Wade House Museum

excerpt: Museum in the 19th-century home of a Civil War soldier's family, exploring the civilian experience.
detail_description: The Shriver House Museum is a historic site located in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania. It was the 19th-century home of a Civil War soldier's family and offers an immersive experience into the civilian life during and after the battle. The house, originally built with an adjacent building for a saloon and bowling alley, has been restored to its period accuracy. Visitors can take a guided tour to learn about the Shriver family's experiences during those fateful days in July.
name: Shriver House Museum at Gettysburg

excerpt: Resting place for 3,512 Union soldiers, dedicated in 1863 with Lincoln's Gettysburg Address.
detail_description: Gettysburg National Cemetery is a solemn resting place for 3,512 Union soldiers and was dedicated in 1863 with Lincoln's Gettysburg Address. The area offers a glimpse into the challenging conditions faced by soldiers during the Civil War, carrying heavy loads and enduring harsh elements. Visitors can explore the roughly 3-mile Gettysburg Trail, a paved walking trail that connects the Visitor Center to important battlefield locations, offering serene woodland surroundings and welcome shade on hot days.
name: Gettysburg National Cemetery
address: National Park Service Museum and Visitor Center, 1195 Baltimore Pike, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

excerpt: Museum explaining the results & aftermath of the Battle of Gettysburg & President Lincoln's address.
detail_description: The David Wills House, situated on Lincoln Square in Gettysburg, is a museum that offers insights into the aftermath of the Battle of Gettysburg and President Lincoln's historic address. Managed by the National Park Service since 2009, this historical site showcases exhibits about the local community, the Gettysburg National Cemetery, and Lincoln's visit. Visitors can explore two rooms restored to their late 1863 appearance, including the bedroom where Lincoln stayed and finalized his speech.
name: David Wills House

excerpt: Cozy rooms with 19th-century style in a historic B&B with an American alehouse & a restaurant.
detail_description: Step into the 19th-century charm of Dobbin House Tavern, a historic bed and breakfast featuring cozy rooms and an American alehouse. Originally built for Reverend Alexander Dobbin, this establishment is now a premier Gettysburg attraction. The candlelit elegance of the restaurant offers superior food and gracious service that transports guests back in time. The Springhouse Tavern provides a more intimate dining experience, while the Abigail Adams Ballroom caters to larger gatherings.
name: Dobbin House Tavern

excerpt: Diorama of the Battle of Gettysburg with over 20,000 pieces, plus a 30-minute light & audio show.
detail_description: The Gettysburg Diorama is an extraordinary attraction that brings the historic Battle of Gettysburg to life through a stunning miniature display. Comprising over 20,000 meticulously hand-painted figures, including soldiers, horses, and cannons, this diorama offers a comprehensive view of the entire 6,000-acre battlefield. Visitors can immerse themselves in a captivating 30-minute light and audio show that narrates the dramatic events of the three-day battle from start to finish.
name: Gettysburg Diorama & History Center

excerpt: Historical spot with self-guided tours features a re-creation of the Battle of Gettysburg & more.
detail_description: The Gettysburg Heritage Center is a historical site that offers self-guided tours and aims to educate visitors about the Battle of Gettysburg. Through artifacts, documents, and interactive displays, the center provides insight into the impact of the battle on the community. It features unique accounts of how locals experienced one of the Civil War's most significant battles near their homes and farms.
name: Gettysburg Heritage Center

excerpt: More than 4,000 artifacts chronicling various American wars with several exhibits & a gift shop.
detail_description: The Gettysburg Museum of History is a treasure trove for history enthusiasts, boasting over 4,000 artifacts spanning various American wars and historical periods. From a Confederate flag used at the First Battle of Bull Run to former President Abraham Lincoln's wallet, the museum offers an eclectic collection that includes an Egyptian mummy head, Saddam Hussein's dining set, and Adolf Hitler's footstool.
name: Gettysburg Museum of History

detail_description: Savor Gettysburg Food Tours offers a delightful three-hour walking tour that takes you through historic streets, showcasing cultural highlights and introducing you to seven unique eateries. Suitable for all fitness levels, the tour covers about one mile and includes visits to an old historic tavern, an exotic ethnic restaurant, a family-owned bistro, and more.
name: Savor Gettysburg Food Tours

excerpt: Handmade dioramas with cat soldiers depict key battles & scenes in a historic former orphanage.
detail_description: Discover the unique and historically accurate dioramas at Civil War Tails at the Homestead Diorama Museum, where handmade miniature cat soldiers depict key battles and scenes from the Civil War. This museum offers a fascinating look into this pivotal period in American history, showcasing weaponry, uniforms, and personal effects from both sides of the conflict. Visitors can also explore other nearby attractions such as Mister Ed's Elephant Museum & Candy Emporium and the Eastern Museum of Motor Racing for a well-rounded experience.
name: Civil War Tails at the Homestead Diorama Museum

excerpt: Gettysburg is a borough and town in the U.S. state of Pennsylvania. It’s known for Gettysburg National Battlefield, site of a turning point in the Civil War, now part of Gettysburg National Military Park. The park also includes the Gettysburg Museum and Visitor Center, displaying Civil War artifacts, and Gettysburg National Cemetery, where a memorial marks the site of Abraham Lincoln’s 1863 Gettysburg Address.
detail_description: Gettysburg, located in Pennsylvania, is famous for the Gettysburg National Battlefield, a pivotal site in the Civil War. The battlefield is part of the Gettysburg National Military Park and features the Gettysburg Museum and Visitor Center as well as the Gettysburg National Cemetery, where Abraham Lincoln delivered his historic address in 1863. Additionally, there are accommodations like Battlefield Bed and Breakfast Inn that offer a romantic retreat with various room options.
name: Gettysburg

detail_description: The Children of Gettysburg 1863 museum offers an educational and engaging experience for kids, providing a child-friendly perspective on the Battle of Gettysburg. The exhibits allow children to empathize with the experiences of young people during the Civil War, incorporating interactive elements to maintain their interest. Located in the historic Rupp House, which was home to a family during the battle, this museum shares compelling stories of children and young adults from that time.
name: Children of Gettysburg 1863®

detail_description: Ghostly Images of Gettysburg offers nightly 90-minute walking tours that take visitors inside the Jennie Wade House or Haunted Orphanage, both known for their ghostly activity. The Haunted Orphanage is particularly chilling, as it was once a place where innocent children suffered at the hands of a cruel matron. These locations have been featured on popular television shows and attract many brave souls. In addition to regular tours, Ghostly Images also offers specialty tours throughout the year.
name: Ghostly Images of Gettysburg

detail_description: Nestled in the lively area of Lincoln Square, The Inn at Lincoln Square offers a cozy retreat in the heart of town. Located within walking distance to the Gettysburg Battlefield and surrounded by local nightlife and activities, this Georgian-style inn provides various accommodation options. Downtown Gettysburg is brimming with shops, boutiques, cafes, and restaurants leading up to historic Lincoln Square. Visitors can explore an array of offerings from clothing and fine arts to collectibles and home decor.
name: Lincoln Square

excerpt: Historic theater space with retro charm offers live music acts, musicals, comedians & classic films.
detail_description: The Majestic Theater, a historic venue with a retro allure, has been hosting live music acts, musicals, comedians, and classic films since its opening in 1925. Once the largest vaudeville and silent movie theater in south-central Pennsylvania, it gained fame in the 1950s when President Dwight D. Eisenhower and his wife Mamie frequented performances there.
name: Majestic Theater

detail_description: Evergreen Cemetery, established in 1854 by Civil War survivor David McConaughy, is a historic resting place for notable figures like theologian Samuel S. Schmucker and Congressman Edward McPherson. It also holds the grave of Jennie Wade, the only civilian killed in the Battle of Gettysburg. The cemetery is a significant site filled with history related to the battle and local townspeople.
name: Evergreen Cemetery

detail_description: If you're a fan of the historical theme, 1863 Escape Room is definitely worth checking out. The escape room is themed around the Battle of Gettysburg and is very well designed and challenging. The staff are very friendly and helpful, making it a great experience for groups.
name: 1863 Escape Room

detail_description: Explore the historic Gettysburg Battlefield on horseback with Confederate Trails of Gettysburg Guided Horseback Tours. Ride through tranquil wooded paths and open to panoramic views of history, feeling transported back in time as you follow the Confederate lines with knowledgeable staff. The well-behaved and responsive horses make for a gentle ride, enhancing the experience of learning about the battle.
name: Confederate Trails of Gettysburg Guided Horseback Tours
address: Youth Group Campground Entrance McMillian Woods Youth Campground GNMP, W Confederate Ave, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

detail_description: Gettysburg Battlefield, also known as the Gettysburg National Military Park, is a significant historical site that played a pivotal role in the Civil War. The battlefield offers free self-guided tours across its 9,000-acre expanse and provides various guided tour options for visitors. One notable area within the battlefield is Lee’s Headquarters, also referred to as the 143rd's Last Stand.
name: Gettysburg Battlefield: Lee’s Headquarters
